sequentialTasks.description:
In [internal/builtin/fetch/fetch.go], the Require function evaluates adapter.Loop().Promisify unconditionally at module load time (lines 39-40). If adapter is nil, this causes a segfault. Fix: wrap both exports.Set calls in if adapter != nil guard, matching the exec.go pattern at internal/builtin/exec/exec.go lines 76-78:

if adapter != nil {
    _ = exports.Set("fetch", jsFetch(runtime, adapter, adapter.Loop().Promisify))
    _ = exports.Set("sseReader", jsSSEReader(runtime, adapter, adapter.Loop().Promisify))
}

Note: When adapter IS nil, the module still loads (exec is available, spawn is not). This matches expected behavior from pr_split_test.go which passes nil.

In [internal/builtin/mcpmod/mcp.go], the Require function evaluates adapter.Loop().Promisify unconditionally at module load time (line 32). Fix: wrap the exports.Set call in if adapter != nil guard:

if adapter != nil {
    _ = exports.Set("createServer", jsCreateServer(runtime, adapter, adapter.Loop().Promisify))
}

Verify: go test -short ./internal/builtin/mcpmod/... passes.

In [internal/builtin/mcpcallbackmod/mcpcallback.go], the Require function evaluates adapter.Loop().Promisify unconditionally at module load time (line 140). Fix: wrap the exports.Set call in if adapter != nil guard:

if adapter != nil {
    _ = exports.Set("MCPCallback", jsCallbackFactory(rt, adapter, adapter.Loop().Promisify))
}

Verify: go test -short ./internal/builtin/mcpcallbackmod/... passes.
